, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Salins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Latvian Arturs.","Latvian (<b>Saliņš</b>): topographic name for someone living on an island, derived from <i>sala</i> ‘island’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gaucher","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Armand, Francoise, Jacques, Laurette, Lucien, Philippe.","French:","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Walhari</i>, composed of the elements <i>walh</i> ‘stranger’ and <i>hari</i> ‘army’."],"variants":[{"name":"Coetzee","meanings":["Afrikaans: probably an altered form of Dutch <b>Goetzee</b>, which is of French Huguenot origin, probably from   Gaucher  . Alternatively, <i>Coetzee</i> may be an altered form of Dutch <b>Kuzee</b>, a habitational name recorded in the 16th century as <i>Cudsee</i> and <i>Cutsee</i>, from a toponym located in Zeeland, which may be interpreted as <i>Cut's-see</i> ‘watercourse of Cudo’.","History: Dirk Coetzee, born in Kampen in the Netherlands around 1655, died in Cape Town in 1725."]}]},{"name":"III","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Yuko, Aiko, Hideaki, Hiroki, Hiroyuki, Isamu, Kaoru, Katsumi, Keiichiro, Kenji, Masako, Masayuki.","Japanese: variously written, sometimes with characters used phonetically; the most probable meanings are 仁井 ‘benevolent well’, 新居 ‘new residence’, or 新井 ‘new well’. It is not common in Japan."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gaucher III de Salins was born in 1088 as the son of